* event handler

"window.onlode"  an event handler that executes a script once the entire page 
(including all its resources such as images, CSS files, etc.) has loaded.

code :

window.onload = function() {
    // Code to execute after the page has fully loaded
    console.log("Page loaded!");
};

example :

<script>
    // run this function when the document is loaded
    window.onload = function(){
      // create a couple of elements in an otherwise empty HTML page
      const heading = document.createElement("h1");
      const headingText = document.createTextNode("Big Head!");
      heading.appendChild(headingText);
      document.body.appendChild(heading);
    };
  </script>


# this event handler creates a variable "heading" which will create a new element h1 using
 the createElement("h1")

# "headingText = document.createTextNode("Big Head!")" creates a text "BIg Head"using the createTextNode

# ".appendChild(heading)" this will append the textNode to the heading as a child of <h1> element